&quot;Pitchfork&quot; Ben Tillman was <b>not</b> the founder of Clemson. 

As governor, and a member of the first board of trustees, Tillman was very active in the college's establishment and management, however, the founder was farmer, engineer, and statesman <b>Thomas Green Clemson, IV</b> (1807-1888) whose will called for the establishment of Clemson Agricultural College of South Carolina &quot;for the benefit of the agricultural and mechanical classes principally, and shall be free of costs to the pupils, as far as the means derived from the endowment hereinafter provided and the use of the land may permit.&quot;  

See <a href="http://www.clemson.edu/about/history/will.html" rel="nofollow">www.clemson.edu/about/history/will.html</a> and <a href="http://www.clemson.edu/about/history/ourfounder.html" rel="nofollow">www.clemson.edu/about/history/ourfounder.html</a>
